        {{! ---- CORE TECHNOLOGIES ---- }}
        <div class="section-divider mb-4">
          <span class="section-label">CORE TECHNOLOGIES</span>
        </div>

        <div class="steps-container mb-5">

          <div class="step-card" data-step-name="Junction open-source CMS AI database blueprint">
            <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
              <span class="step-badge">1</span>
              <span class="step-title">Junction</span>
              <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <p>
                Junction is an open-source, AI-powered tool that transforms your idea into a
                structured database. It enables you to host all your files, data and APIs in one
                secure location, ensuring complete control, ownership and privacy for your project.
              </p>
              <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>What it does</strong></h6>
                      <ul class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
                        <li>Generates database tables, admin interfaces and API endpoints from a single <code>types.json</code> blueprint</li>
                        <li>Provides a browser-based no-code UI for managing content, schemas and users</li>
                        <li>Hosts files, data and API — all in one place</li>
                        <li>Connects to any frontend via the Tribe JSON:API</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>How it fits in</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        Junction is the <em>no-code control layer</em> that sits on top of
                        <code>tribe-core</code>. Developers define the data model in
                        <code>types.json</code>; Junction reads that blueprint and generates
                        everything else — database schema, admin UI, REST API.
                      </p>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-0">
                        Access it locally at
                        <a href="http://junction.localhost:12002" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">junction.localhost:12002</a>
                        or via the cloud at <a href="https://junction.express" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">junction.express</a>.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="alert alert-light mt-3 mb-0 small">
                <i class="fa-brands fa-github me-1"></i>
                <strong>Further reading:</strong>
                <a href="https://github.com/tribe-framework/tribe" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/tribe-framework/tribe</a>
                &mdash; the main Tribe repository that ships Junction together with all Docker services.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step-card" data-step-name="tribe-core PHP headless CMS JSON API Composer">
            <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
              <span class="step-badge">2</span>
              <span class="step-title">tribe-core</span>
              <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <p>
                <code>tribe-core</code> is the PHP package that powers the backend. It is a
                headless CMS framework providing a JSON:API for dynamic content management with
                flexible content types, authentication, and file handling. It is installed and
                managed via <strong>Composer</strong>.
              </p>
              <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-md-4">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Core classes</strong></h6>
                      <dl class="small mb-0">
                        <dt><code>\Tribe\Core</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">Object CRUD and search</dd>
                        <dt><code>\Tribe\API</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">RESTful JSON:API handler</dd>
                        <dt><code>\Tribe\Config</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">Content type definitions</dd>
                        <dt><code>\Tribe\Uploads</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">File upload &amp; image processing</dd>
                        <dt><code>\Tribe\MySQL</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-0">Database abstraction</dd>
                      </dl>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-4">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Single-table design</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        All content lives in one <code>data</code> table. Every object has
                        an <code>id</code>, a JSON <code>content</code> field, a <code>type</code>,
                        a <code>slug</code>, and a <code>content_privacy</code> level
                        (<code>public</code>, <code>private</code>, <code>draft</code>,
                        <code>pending</code>, <code>sent</code>).
                      </p>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-0">
                        This flat structure makes it trivial to add new content types without
                        database migrations.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-4">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Composer</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        Composer is PHP's dependency manager. <code>tribe-core</code> is
                        installed into any PHP project with:
                      </p>
                      <div class="command-block mb-2">
                        <button class="btn btn-sm copy-btn-block" onclick="copyCmd('composer require tribe-framework/tribe-core', this)" type="button">Copy</button>
                        <code>composer require tribe-framework/tribe-core</code>
                      </div>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-0">
                        The Docker image runs <code>composer install</code> automatically on
                        startup. In Loom mode, <code>composer install</code> runs once for the
                        shared <code>tribe-base/</code> and is mounted read-only across all threads.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="alert alert-light mt-3 mb-0 small">
                <i class="fa-brands fa-github me-1"></i>
                <strong>Further reading:</strong>
                <a href="https://github.com/tribe-framework/tribe-core" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/tribe-framework/tribe-core</a>
                &mdash; full PHP class documentation, API reference and authentication levels.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step-card" data-step-name="types.json blueprint content types modules fields Junction">
            <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
              <span class="step-badge">3</span>
              <span class="step-title">types.json</span>
              <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <p>
                <code>types.json</code> is the core blueprint file for Junction. It defines every
                data type (called <em>Tracks</em> in Junction's UI) and every field within each
                type (called <em>Modules</em>). Junction reads this file to automatically generate
                the database schema, admin interface and API endpoints.
              </p>
              <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Key concepts</strong></h6>
                      <dl class="small mb-0">
                        <dt>Type / Track</dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">A content entity (e.g. <code>post</code>, <code>user</code>, <code>product</code>). Defined by a <code>slug</code>, <code>name</code>, <code>plural</code>, and a <code>modules</code> array.</dd>
                        <dt>Module / Field</dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">An individual field on a type. Defined by <code>input_slug</code>, <code>input_type</code>, <code>var_type</code>, and optional properties like <code>input_primary</code>, <code>input_unique</code>, <code>linked_type</code>.</dd>
                        <dt>linked_type</dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-0">Creates a relationship between two types. The API automatically resolves and inlines the linked object with a <code>__linked</code> suffix on the field.</dd>
                      </dl>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Where it lives</strong></h6>
                      <table class="table table-sm table-borderless mb-0 small">
                        <tbody>
                          <tr>
                            <td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-3">config/types.json</td>
                            <td class="text-muted">Committed to the repo — the source of truth</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-3">uploads/types/*.json</td>
                            <td class="text-muted">Overrides uploaded dynamically via Junction</td>
                          </tr>
                          <tr>
                            <td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-3">Remote URL</td>
                            <td class="text-muted">GitHub repository blueprint — loadable remotely</td>
                          </tr>
                        </tbody>
                      </table>
                      <p class="small text-muted mt-2 mb-0">
                        The <code>webapp/0</code> API endpoint always returns the currently active types configuration.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="alert alert-light mt-3 mb-0 small">
                <i class="fa-brands fa-github me-1"></i>
                <strong>Further reading:</strong>
                <a href="https://github.com/tribe-framework/types.json" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/tribe-framework/types.json</a>
                &mdash; full field reference, valid <code>input_type</code> values, relationship patterns, and SEO module conventions.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step-card" data-step-name="ember-tribe EmberJS addon npm node frontend">
            <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
              <span class="step-badge">4</span>
              <span class="step-title">ember-tribe &amp; the Frontend Stack</span>
              <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <p>
                <code>ember-tribe</code> is an EmberJS addon that connects your frontend
                application to the Tribe API. It bridges backend data structures and frontend
                development, and helps you build an Ember app directly from your
                <code>types.json</code> blueprint. It is installed and managed via
                <strong>npm</strong>, which in turn requires <strong>Node.js</strong>.
              </p>
              <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-md-4">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Node.js &amp; npm</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        <strong>Node.js</strong> is the JavaScript runtime that powers all Ember
                        tooling. <strong>npm</strong> is the Node Package Manager used to install
                        frontend dependencies including <code>ember-tribe</code> itself.
                      </p>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-0">
                        Tribe requires Node.js (latest LTS). Use NVM to manage Node versions.
                        See the Prerequisites page for installation steps.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-4">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>ember-tribe features</strong></h6>
                      <ul class="small text-muted mb-0 ps-3">
                        <li>Auto-generates EmberData models from backend type definitions via the <code>types</code> service</li>
                        <li>Pre-installs Bootstrap 5, FontAwesome 6, animate.css, video.js, swiper, howler, sortablejs, papaparse</li>
                        <li>Includes 30+ built-in layout and interactive components</li>
                        <li>Ships with <code>storylang</code> CLI for spec management</li>
                      </ul>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-4">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Data access pattern</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        All backend fields are accessed via a <code>modules</code> object.
                        Only <code>.id</code> and <code>.slug</code> are direct properties.
                      </p>
                      <code class="small d-block bg-light p-2 rounded">
                        post.modules.title<br>
                        post.modules.content_privacy<br>
                        post.id &nbsp;&nbsp;// direct<br>
                        post.slug // direct
                      </code>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="alert alert-light mt-3 mb-0 small">
                <i class="fa-brands fa-github me-1"></i>
                <strong>Further reading:</strong>
                <a href="https://github.com/tribe-framework/ember-tribe" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">github.com/tribe-framework/ember-tribe</a>
                &mdash; full development guide, EmberData integration, component architecture and deployment instructions.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step-card" data-step-name="storylang CLI JSON spec frontend blueprint routes components services">
            <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
              <span class="step-badge">5</span>
              <span class="step-title">storylang</span>
              <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <p>
                <code>storylang</code> is two things in one: a <strong>CLI tool</strong> that ships
                inside <code>ember-tribe</code>, and a <strong>JSON specification file</strong>
                (<code>config/storylang.json</code>) that defines the complete structure of a
                frontend application. Think of it as <code>types.json</code>'s counterpart — where
                <code>types.json</code> describes the backend data model, <code>storylang.json</code>
                describes the frontend implementation.
              </p>
              <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>storylang.json sections</strong></h6>
                      <dl class="small mb-0">
                        <dt><code>types</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">Maps backend types to the routes, components and services that consume them</dd>
                        <dt><code>routes</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">Route definitions including tracked vars, query params, actions and component usage</dd>
                        <dt><code>helpers</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">Pure template functions — input/output defined, no side effects</dd>
                        <dt><code>modifiers</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">DOM manipulation and third-party library initialisations</dd>
                        <dt><code>services</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-1">App-wide business logic and shared state</dd>
                        <dt><code>components</code></dt>
                        <dd class="text-muted mb-0">Reusable UI components with tracked vars, args and actions</dd>
                      </dl>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>storylang CLI</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        Run from inside your Ember app directory to scan the
                        <code>app/</code> folder and sync <code>storylang.json</code> from
                        the actual project files:
                      </p>
                      <div class="command-block mb-2">
                        <button class="btn btn-sm copy-btn-block" onclick="copyCmd('node storylang', this)" type="button">Copy</button>
                        <code>node storylang</code>
                      </div>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-0">
                        Run periodically to keep the spec in sync as the project evolves.
                        <code>storylang.json</code> is the single source of truth for what
                        a frontend does — ideal as AI context (see the AI tab).
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="alert alert-info mt-3 mb-0 small">
                <strong>Design principle:</strong> Understand
                <em>Types → Routes → Controllers → Helpers → Modifiers → Services → Components</em>
                — always begin with data, then define routes, then work outward to components.
                <code>storylang.json</code> enforces this order explicitly.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step-card" data-step-name="EditorJS WYSIWYG rich text editor Junction input type">
            <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
              <span class="step-badge">6</span>
              <span class="step-title">EditorJS</span>
              <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <p>
                EditorJS is the WYSIWYG block-based rich text editor used as one of Junction's
                HTML5 Input Types. When a field in <code>types.json</code> is defined with
                <code>"input_type": "editorjs"</code>, Junction renders a full block editor
                for that field in its admin UI.
              </p>
              <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>How to declare it</strong></h6>
                      <code class="small d-block bg-light p-2 rounded">
                        {<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;"input_slug": "body",<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;"input_type": "editorjs",<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;"var_type": "array",<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;"input_placeholder": "Type content here"<br>
                        }
                      </code>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>How it stores data</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        EditorJS saves content as a JSON array of blocks — each block has a
                        <code>type</code> (paragraph, header, image, list, etc.) and associated
                        data. The <code>var_type</code> must be <code>array</code> to store
                        this structure correctly.
                      </p>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-0">
                        Every <code>types.json</code> blueprint must include at least one type
                        with an <code>editorjs</code> module per Junction's blueprint rules.
                      </p>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="step-card" data-step-name="HLS HTTP Live Streaming video adaptive upload tribe-core">
            <div class="step-header" onclick="toggleStep(this)">
              <span class="step-badge">7</span>
              <span class="step-title">HLS (HTTP Live Streaming)</span>
              <i class="fa-solid fa-chevron-down step-chevron"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <p>
                When a video file is uploaded via <code>uploads.php</code>, <code>tribe-core</code>
                automatically converts it to HLS (HTTP Live Streaming) format using FFmpeg. HLS
                splits the video into small segments and generates playlists at multiple quality
                levels, enabling adaptive bitrate streaming — the player switches quality in
                real time based on the viewer's connection speed.
              </p>
              <div class="row g-3">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Quality levels generated</strong></h6>
                      <table class="table table-sm table-borderless mb-0 small">
                        <tbody>
                          <tr><td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-2">xl</td><td class="text-muted">3840×2160 — 4K (15 Mbps)</td></tr>
                          <tr><td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-2">lg</td><td class="text-muted">1920×1080 — Full HD (8 Mbps)</td></tr>
                          <tr><td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-2">md</td><td class="text-muted">1280×720 — HD (4 Mbps)</td></tr>
                          <tr><td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-2">sm</td><td class="text-muted">960×540 — (2 Mbps)</td></tr>
                          <tr><td class="font-monospace text-nowrap pe-2">xs</td><td class="text-muted">640×360 — (1 Mbps)</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                      </table>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                  <div class="card method-item h-100">
                    <div class="card-body">
                      <h6 class="mb-2"><strong>Accessing HLS in the frontend</strong></h6>
                      <p class="small text-muted mb-2">
                        After a successful video upload, the response includes an
                        <code>hls</code> object with a <code>.m3u8</code> master playlist URL.
                        Use the pre-installed <code>video.js</code> player in
                        <code>ember-tribe</code> to play it.
                      </p>
                      <code class="small d-block bg-light p-2 rounded">
                        data.file.hls.url &nbsp;// master playlist<br>
                        data.file.hls.qualities // ['xl','lg','md','sm','xs']
                      </code>
                    </div>
                  </div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

        {{! ---- GLOSSARY ---- }}
        <div class="section-divider mb-4">
          <span class="section-label">GLOSSARY</span>
        </div>

        <div class="row g-3 mb-5">
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card method-item h-100">
              <div class="card-body">
                <h6 class="mb-3"><strong>Core</strong></h6>
                <dl class="mb-0">
                  <dt>Tribe</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">PHP content/app framework — the core backend and UI engine. Serves content, handles APIs, and runs the application layer.</dd>
                  <dt>Junction</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">No-code CMS layer that connects to Tribe via API. Manages content, schemas and users through a browser UI.</dd>
                  <dt>tribe-core</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">The Composer PHP package at the heart of Tribe. Provides <code>\Tribe\Core</code>, <code>\Tribe\API</code>, <code>\Tribe\Config</code>, <code>\Tribe\Uploads</code> and <code>\Tribe\MySQL</code> classes.</dd>
                  <dt>ember-tribe</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">The npm EmberJS addon that connects a frontend app to the Tribe API. Auto-generates EmberData models from <code>types.json</code>.</dd>
                  <dt>Docker</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">Containerisation platform. <code>docker-compose.yml</code> defines all services, networks and volumes.</dd>
                  <dt>.env</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-0">Environment file holding secrets and config — DB passwords, ports, project name. Never committed to Git.</dd>
                </dl>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="col-md-6">
            <div class="card method-item h-100">
              <div class="card-body">
                <h6 class="mb-3"><strong>Data &amp; Content</strong></h6>
                <dl class="mb-0">
                  <dt>types.json</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">The blueprint file. Defines every content type (Track) and its fields (Modules). Junction reads this to generate the database, admin UI and API.</dd>
                  <dt>storylang.json</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">Frontend specification file at <code>config/storylang.json</code>. Defines routes, components, services, helpers and modifiers. Synced via the <code>node storylang</code> CLI.</dd>
                  <dt>Track</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">Junction's UI name for a content type (e.g. Post, User, Product). Defined as a key in <code>types.json</code>.</dd>
                  <dt>Module</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">Junction's UI name for an individual field on a Track. Corresponds to an entry in the <code>modules</code> array within <code>types.json</code>.</dd>
                  <dt>EditorJS</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-2">WYSIWYG block editor used as Junction's <code>editorjs</code> input type for rich text fields.</dd>
                  <dt>HLS</dt>
                  <dd class="text-muted small mb-0">HTTP Live Streaming. Video uploads are auto-converted to HLS by <code>tribe-core</code>, producing adaptive multi-quality streams.</dd>
                </dl>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
